This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.SD (Sound) as it deals with speaker diarisation systems that cluster audio segments. It also involves the use of speaker embeddings such as i-vectors and d-vectors, which are commonly used in speech processing. 

It could also belong to cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it involves natural language processing tasks such as speaker identification and clustering. 

The use of self-attentive structures suggests that it could belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as self-attention has been widely used in deep learning models for various tasks. 

It could also belong to cs.SI (Signal Processing) as it involves processing audio signals to extract speaker embeddings and cluster them. 

Finally, it could belong to cs.SDQ (Sound and Music Computing) as it deals with the processing of audio signals for speaker diarisation, which is a subfield of sound and music computing.
